I have some simple code that opens a request to an SSE server and waits for messages. All works fine until the connection to server is interrupted (server restart, connectivity issues, etc).

When this happens, StreamReader.ReadLineAsync starts to read "empty" lines instead of simply throw because the underlining stream was closed.

The code is similar to the following:

```cs
var request = new HttpRequestMessage {
	Method = HttpMethod.Get,
	RequestUri = _targetUri
};

request.Headers.Accept.Add(new MediaTypeWithQualityHeaderValue("text/event-stream"));
request.Headers.Connection.Add("keep-alive");
var response = await _client.SendAsync(request, HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead, token).ConfigureAwait(false);
var content = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync().ConfigureAwait(false);
using (var sr = new StreamReader(content, Encoding.UTF8)) {
	while (true){
		var line = await sr.ReadLineAsync().ConfigureAwait(false);
		...do something with line...
	}
}
```

The thing is: sometimes it works (when the connection closes, the ReadLineAsync throws), but sometimes it doesn't (ReadLineAsync continues to return empty results). On my machine I can reproduce this 50% of the time (so, it's quite easy to reproduce). If I put fiddler in the middle, it works 100% of the time.

Right now I detect this by counting the number of empty results and if it's too high (100 in my case) I simply break out of the loop, but that sounds more like a hack to me.

Notes:
_client is a reference to a global HttpClient that I use across the application. It is initialized as
```cs
new HttpClient(new HttpClientHandler {
	AllowAutoRedirect = false,
	AutomaticDecompression = DecompressionMethods.GZip | DecompressionMethods.Deflate
}) {
	Timeout = Timeout.InfiniteTimeSpan
};
```

