Regex.Escape("[]") produces "\\[]". When used in a pattern as is, it works as expected.
```C#
            {
                // Works.
                Regex pattern = new Regex(Regex.Escape("[]"));
                Match match = pattern.Match("[]");
                bool ok = match.Success; // Match
            }
            {
                // Works.
                Regex pattern = new Regex("\\[\\]");
                Match match = pattern.Match("[]");
                bool ok = match.Success; // Match
            }
```

However, when used inside a character class, it doesn't work as expected.
```C#
            {
                // Doesn't work. "[\\[]]" doesn't match either "[" or "]"
                Regex pattern = new Regex("["+Regex.Escape("[]")+"]");
                var matches = pattern.Matches("aa]aa");
                bool assertOk = matches.Count == 1; // no matches
            }
            {
                // Works with pattern "[\\[\\]]"
                Regex pattern = new Regex("[\\[\\]]");
                var matches = pattern.Matches("aa]aa");
                bool assertOk = matches.Count == 1; // matched
            }
```

Character class is closed by first "]". The obvious fix is to escape the "]" as "\\\\]".

